---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { loadCorpus } from "../domain/corpus/load-corpus";

const corpus = await loadCorpus();
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Methodology"
  description="How GraphRoots defines relationships, assigns direction, evaluates evidence, represents disagreement, and reviews its evolving corpus."
  canonicalPath="/methodology"
>
  <article class="shell methodology">
    <header class="reading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Methodology · Corpus {corpus.metadata.version}</p>
      <h1>Every arrow is a claim.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        GraphRoots treats musical transmission as heterogeneous,
        evidence-dependent, and open to revision. Mentorship, membership,
        performance, adaptation, shared context, and historical comparison are
        distinct relationships and are not treated as interchangeable forms of
        influence.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="method-grid">
      <aside>
        <nav aria-label="Methodology sections">
          <a href="#scope">Scope</a>
          <a href="#qualification">Qualification</a>
          <a href="#direction">Direction</a>
          <a href="#evidence">Evidence</a>
          <a href="#sources">Sources</a>
          <a href="#disagreement">Disagreement</a>
          <a href="#limits">Limits</a>
          <a href="#review">Review</a>
          <a href="#releases">Releases</a>
        </nav>
      </aside>

      <div class="reading prose">
        <section id="scope">
          <h2>Scope and unit of record</h2>
          <p>
            GraphRoots is a curated and versioned knowledge graph of musical
            transmission. Its entities may include artists, ensembles,
            traditions, recordings, compositions, places, scenes, institutions,
            events, and revival movements.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each relationship is an atomic proposition connecting two entities.
            It records one specific claim that can be expressed in plain
            language, supported by citations, and reviewed independently from
            other relationships.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="qualification">
          <h2>What qualifies</h2>
          <p>
            A relationship qualifies for the reviewed corpus when its meaning
            can be represented by a controlled relationship type, its endpoints
            are clearly identified, and its supporting evidence and limitations
            can be described.
          </p>
          <p>
            GraphRoots does not treat <code>influenced</code> as a sufficient relationship
            type in the reviewed corpus. A claim should instead identify the mechanism
            involved, such as mentorship, collaboration, adaptation, performance,
            repertoire transmission, institutional association, migration, revival,
            or documented stylistic influence.
          </p>
          <p>
            Legacy untyped links and explicit artist co-mentions found in a
            cited biography may appear temporarily as dashed provisional
            pathways while they await classification, corroboration, or removal.
            A co-mention shows that one artist's biography places the other in
            its account; it does not by itself establish influence or causation.
            Provisional paths are excluded from the reviewed public dataset.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="direction">
          <h2>How direction works</h2>
          <p>
            Direction follows the meaning of the relationship predicate. In
            <code>A mentored B</code>, A is the mentor and B is the person
            mentored. In <code>A member_of B</code>, A is the member and B is
            the ensemble. Predicate direction does not necessarily imply
            causation or historical importance.
          </p>
          <p>
            Symmetric relationships, such as a shared scene or reciprocal
            collaboration, are stored and displayed without an arbitrary causal
            direction. They are not rendered as one-way influence arrows.
          </p>
          <p>
            Untyped provisional records use neutral endpoints and an
            <code>undetermined</code> orientation. They appear without arrows, and
            visitors can switch from the default exploratory graph to a reviewed-only
            view.
          </p>
          <p>
            The complete GraphRoots knowledge graph may contain cycles. The
            historical transmission DAG is a derived analytical projection
            containing only relationships that are both asymmetric and
            temporally ordered. Membership, symmetric association, reciprocal
            collaboration, and retrospective revival are excluded from that
            projection unless a separate directed transmission claim is
            documented.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="evidence">
          <h2>Evidence categories</h2>
          <dl>
            <div>
              <dt>Directly documented</dt>
              <dd>
                Supported by direct testimony, correspondence, interviews,
                recording documentation, contractual records, contemporary
                reporting, or other primary or near-primary evidence.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Historically corroborated</dt>
              <dd>
                Supported by multiple credible and substantially independent
                historical sources, even when direct testimony does not survive.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Contextual or inferential</dt>
              <dd>
                Supported by repertoire, chronology, geography, institutional
                association, shared performance context, or another indirect
                line of evidence that warrants a qualified connection.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Interpretive or debated</dt>
              <dd>
                Represents a plausible interpretation, disputed attribution, or
                non-continuous historical comparison whose uncertainty is part
                of the record.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
          <p>
            These categories describe the basis and strength of support. They
            are not calibrated numerical probabilities, and they should not be
            converted mechanically into certainty scores.
          </p>
          <p>
            Evidence category, relationship type, editorial review status, and
            dispute status are recorded separately.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="sources">
          <h2>Sources and citation policy</h2>
          <p>
            Every reviewed public relationship must cite at least one
            identifiable source. Citations should include page numbers, archival
            identifiers, recording details, interview dates, or timecodes
            whenever these are available.
          </p>
          <p>
            Primary sources are preferred for direct historical claims, but they
            are not treated as automatically complete or impartial. Secondary
            scholarship is evaluated for its methods, proximity to the events,
            and dependence on earlier accounts.
          </p>
          <p>
            Several publications repeating the same unsupported account do not
            constitute independent corroboration. When sources conflict, the
            disagreement and the basis of each interpretation are recorded
            rather than silently resolved.
          </p>
          <p>
            A linked artist mention in an English Wikipedia biography may
            support a provisional discovery path when GraphRoots records the
            exact page revision and paragraph locator. That single source is a
            discovery aid, not independent corroboration, and cannot make the
            relationship reviewed without further editorial assessment.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="disagreement">
          <h2>Disagreement</h2>
          <p>
            A disputed relationship may remain public when the disagreement is
            historically meaningful, adequately sourced, and clearly described.
            Disputed records use distinct styling, carry a visible notice, and
            avoid language that implies established causation.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dispute status does not mean that a record has escaped review. A
            relationship may be both reviewed and disputed when the editorial
            conclusion is that a documented disagreement should remain visible.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="limits">
          <h2>Limits and bias</h2>
          <p>
            GraphRoots is not a complete or authoritative genealogy of the
            blues. The corpus inherits archival, commercial, geographic, and
            institutional biases, including unequal documentation produced by
            segregation, exclusion from recording industries, unequal access to
            distribution, and the later formation of musical canons.
          </p>
          <p>
            Recorded and commercially successful musicians are often easier to
            document than local performers, informal teachers, audiences,
            communities, and collective traditions. The platform therefore
            represents surviving and reviewed evidence, not the full historical
            reality of musical transmission.
          </p>
          <p>
            The absence of an edge means only that the current release does not
            contain a sufficiently defined and supported relationship. It does
            not establish that no historical connection existed.
          </p>
          <p>
            Connection count, path position, centrality, and other graph
            measures describe the current corpus. They are not measures of
            artistic value, originality, cultural importance, or historical
            worth.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="review">
          <h2>Review and correction</h2>
          <p>
            Editorial review status is independent from evidence category and
            dispute status.
          </p>
          <dl>
            <div>
              <dt>Draft</dt>
              <dd>
                An internal record under development. Draft records are not
                included in the public graph or public downloads.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Provisional</dt>
              <dd>
                A partially reviewed record that may appear as a clearly styled
                exploratory pathway. It is excluded from the reviewed dataset,
                public relationship exports, and analytical projections.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Reviewed</dt>
              <dd>
                A record whose type, endpoints, wording, evidence, citations,
                and notices have passed editorial review.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Withdrawn</dt>
              <dd>
                A previously considered or published claim that is no longer
                supported. Its withdrawal remains documented in the changelog,
                but the relationship is excluded from the active graph.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
          <p>
            Reviewed records may also be marked as disputed when the
            disagreement itself has been examined and documented. Records
            requiring substantive correction return to provisional status until
            the necessary review is complete.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="releases">
          <h2>Releases and reproducibility</h2>
          <p>
            The corpus has its own version number, independent from the
            application version. Each public release records additions,
            corrections, reclassifications, disputes, and withdrawals in a
            dedicated changelog.
          </p>
          <p>
            Before release, automated validation checks entity references,
            relationship types, duplicate records, citation requirements,
            temporal consistency, and publication status. Public exports are
            generated from the same reviewed corpus used to build the website.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .methodology {
    padding-block: clamp(3rem, 8vw, 7rem);
  }

  .method-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 12rem minmax(0, 1fr);
    gap: clamp(2rem, 7vw, 7rem);
    margin-top: 3rem;
  }

  .methodology aside nav {
    position: sticky;
    top: calc(var(--site-header-height, 0rem) + 2rem);
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    font-family: var(--font-meta);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .methodology aside a {
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .prose section {
    scroll-margin-top: calc(var(--site-header-height, 0rem) + 2rem);
  }

  .prose section + section {
    margin-top: clamp(3rem, 7vw, 5rem);
  }

  code {
    color: var(--color-gold);
    font-family: var(--font-meta);
  }

  dl {
    margin-block: 1.5rem;
  }

  dl div {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-block: 1rem;
  }

  dl div:first-child {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  dt {
    color: var(--color-gold);
    font-family: var(--font-meta);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  dd {
    margin: 0.35rem 0 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 44rem) {
    .method-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .methodology aside nav {
      position: static;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(8rem, 1fr));
    }
  }
</style>
